## Working with Errors

### Checking Errors

```ruby
article = Article.new
article.valid?  # false
article.invalid?  # true

# Get all errors
article.errors.full_messages
# => ["Title can't be blank", "Body is too short"]

# Get errors for specific attribute
article.errors[:title]
# => ["can't be blank"]

# Check if attribute has errors
article.errors[:title].any?  # true

# Clear errors
article.errors.clear
```

### Adding Custom Errors

```ruby
class Article < ApplicationRecord
  validate :custom_validation
  
  private
  
  def custom_validation
    # Add error to specific attribute
    errors.add(:title, "cannot be 'Test'") if title == 'Test'
    
    # Add error to base (not specific attribute)
    errors.add(:base, "Article must have either body or video")
    
    # Add multiple errors
    if title.blank?
      errors.add(:title, "can't be blank")
      errors.add(:title, "must be present")
    end
  end
end
```

### Error Messages in Views

```erb
<!-- Display all errors -->
<% if @article.errors.any? %>
  <div class="bg-red-100 border border-red-400 text-red-700 px-4 py-3 rounded">
    <h2><%= pluralize(@article.errors.count, "error") %> prohibited this article from being saved:</h2>
    <ul>
      <% @article.errors.full_messages.each do |message| %>
        <li><%= message %></li>
      <% end %>
    </ul>
  </div>
<% end %>

<!-- Display errors for specific field -->
<%= form.text_field :title, class: @article.errors[:title].any? ? 'border-red-500' : '' %>
<% if @article.errors[:title].any? %>
  <p class="text-red-600 text-sm mt-1">
    <%= @article.errors[:title].first %>
  </p>
<% end %>
```

